SIFISO Mvundle can’t read or write but he expresses himself through his art. The 25-year-old from Soweto said his brain was affected by meningitis, which he got in grade 10 due to his HIV status. Despite his difficulties with reading and writing, Sifiso, who has lived most of his life with HIV, is an HIV and Aids counsellor and educator for the Tholulwazi Phakathi organisation. “My art speaks about the dark spaces I have been in as a person living with HIV. “After the deaths of my parents and gogo, I developed anxiety caused by the loss but also by some community members who judged us,” he said. Sifiso said he avoided going out until he met Nonhlanhla Mazaleni, who invited him to join her support group and boot camp. “I had very low self-esteem as I thought I was the only person living with HIV. Nonhlanhla made me live positively.. She is very accommodating because she allows me to use voice note messages on WhatsApp to communicate with the group” When asked how he would celebrate Youth Day on 16 June, Sifiso said he had nothing to celebrate. “I do not have matric or work due to the HIV pandemic. What is the delay in finding a cure or vaccination?” he asked. Nonhlanhla said: “After joining my support group, Sifiso He thought he was the only person living with HIV.gained confidence immediately. I am proud of him.” Sifiso’s cousin, Siphokazi (25), said he wanted to be a teacher but he couldn’t His artwork shows his heartbreak,” he said. When Sifiso is not drawing or providing counselling, he runs a T-shirt printing business called Inja Yami.